snippet.textDisplay:
I mean, the video does have good points. But you guys are forgetting one little thing. Do you guys remember the absolute HUGE petroleum companies that sponsor each team ? Petronas itself is 2x to 3x larger than the VW group. I really don't think its going to be the "end" of F1. Maybe we'll have some changes down the Line but Liberty Media seens to be preparing the Sport to ensure its survival ( like the 2021 cars specs , the utilization of larger Biofuels percentages, the Net Carbon emissions of the whole sport equaling to zero by 2022 and etc. ).

We could also have the opposite effect. If major motorsports categories start using electric only power units and the fans don't like it, F1 could receive a lot of New Fans down the Line.

We also need to adress one major misconception about Eletric Cars. When we compare the car itself it does not generate CO2 emissions, however, the batteries that it runs in are made of Lithium and other metals that are hardly recycled and required a lot of deeply poluting mining operations to be acquired. While it is controversial, I think that investing in Biofuels and "closing" the Carbon Cycle would have better outcomes in fighting for planet wise sustainability.

snippet.textDisplay:
Electric racing fails. Why? Try watching it, no smell, no sound of racing it's just plane boring.

Racing only exists because fans pay to see it and support the sponsors products.

Bottom line, no fuel, no fans, no racing.

The fans will turn out to see an electric race once. After that, never again. It's just to quiet and boring. No sights, no sounds, no smell, no fans.

Drag racing tried it years ago and quickly learned that it simply won't fly with the fans.

Think of your pride and joy muscle car being silent. Takes the fun out of it. No hemi, no super charger no turbo just a nearly silent electric motor sound. Makes driving your challenger kind of pointless.

Just because you can doesn't always mean you should.

Silent, electric racing is doomed to fail before it begins. It's like watching others playing a racing video game.

Honda exiting F1 may have been a big possibility if they had stayed with McLaren. I mean, it could've exited the sport in 2017 after being blasted by both McLaren and Alonso. But the fact they are doing well with Red Bull and Toro Rosso/AlphaTauri means Honda will likely stay in F1 for a foreseeable future.
